## Summary

**Step 1 — Research (4 parallel agents):** All four wrote their reports. They independently converged on a coherent macro narrative, which gave me strong cross-corroboration.

**Step 2 — Verification (VERIFICATION.md, status: PASS):** I caught one apparent red flag up front — Agent 3 framed the Strait of Hormuz as "closed since March, largest oil disruption in history" while reporting oil at only ~$92, which looked contradictory. Since every event here post-dates my Jan 2026 knowledge cutoff, I web-verified **10 key data points** rather than trusting memory. All passed:
- The **Iran war / Hormuz crisis is real** (Operation Epic Fury Feb 28; Strait declared closed Mar 4; ~20% of oil disrupted). The contradiction **resolved** — oil is ~$92 because crude retreated double-digits on repeated reopening optimism + demand-destruction fears, not because the disruption is fake. Both agent framings were facets of the truth.
- May jobs (+172K vs 80K, 4.3%), **Warsh confirmed Fed Chair** (54-45, May 13), June 5 index closes (exact to the decimal), the $1T chip rout, **BTC** >50% below its ~$126K Oct-2025 ATH, **Quantinuum's** $15.7B IPO, oil levels, and the surprisingly-high **$4,340 gold** — all confirmed.
- I also fetched verified 2025 year-end closes to replace Agent 1's estimated YTD figures with exact ones (**SPX +7.9%, Nasdaq +10.6%, Dow +5.8%**).

**Step 3 — Compile (EAGLE_EYE.md):** Led with the regime shift (jobs shock → Fed flips toward a *hike* → chip rout) plus the live Iran/Hormuz weekend escalation as co-lede. Includes a prominent **Weekend & Breaking** section (Day-100 strikes, OPEC+ 4th quota hike, crypto weekend bounce), Scorecard, Sector Heatmap, a tier-accurate **Thesis Watchlist Tracker** (tiers cross-checked against all 9 THESIS files), Fed/Rates, Commodities/FX, Crypto, and a **Week Ahead** using the calendar's exact day headers (no econ tables — left for stamp-calendar.py) with CPI Wednesday framed as the fulcrum, ORCL/ADBE earnings, and the blackout/absences.

One note on remaining soft spots, all explicitly labeled in the report: Sunday-night futures levels weren't retrievable (no number fabricated), and per-sector weekly ETF percentages, exact IG/HY OAS closes, and a few watchlist names (CEG/VST/CCJ/PL/LUNR/LMT) lack name-specific verified weekly moves.
